# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pc-saft
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] In chemistry, the **Avogadro constant**, commonly denoted ***N*A**, is a conversion constant or ratio between an amount of substance and the number of particles that it contains.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The particles in question are any designated elementary entity, such as molecules, atoms, ions, or ion pairs.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] It is an SI defining constant with the exact value 6.02214076×1023 mol−1 (reciprocal mole).
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The numerical value of this constant when expressed in terms of the mole is known as the **Avogadro number**, commonly denoted *N*0.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Both the constant and the number are named after the Italian physicist and chemist Amedeo Avogadro.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The Avogadro constant *N*A is also the factor that converts the average mass *m*(X) of one particle of a substance to its molar mass *M*(X).
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Applying this equation to 12C with an atomic mass of exactly 12 Da and a molar mass of 12 g/mol yields (after rearrangement) the following relation for the Avogadro constant: *N*A = (g/Da) mol−1, making the Avogadro number *N*0 = g/Da.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Historically, this was precisely true, but since the 2019 revision of the SI, the relation is now merely approximate, although equality may still be assumed with high accuracy.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The constant *N*A also relates the molar volume (the volume per mole) of a substance to the average volume nominally occupied by one of its particles, when both are expressed in the same units of volume.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] For example, since the molar volume of water in ordinary conditions is about 18 mL/mol, the volume occupied by one molecule of water is about 18/(6.022×1023) mL, or about 0.030 nm3 (cubic nanometres).
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] For a crystalline substance, it provides as similarly relationship between the volume of a crystal to that of its unit cell.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The Avogadro constant was historically derived from the old definition of the mole as the amount of substance in 12 grams of carbon-12 (12C).
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] By this old definition, the numerical value of the Avogadro constant in mol−1 (the Avogadro number) was a physical constant that had to be determined experimentally.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The redefinition of the mole in 2019, as being the amount of substance consisting of exactly 6.02214076×1023 elementary entities, means that the mass of 1 mole of a substance is now exactly the product of the Avogadro number and the average mass of one of the entities involved.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The dalton, however, is still defined as ⁠1/12⁠ of the mass of a 12C atom, which must be determined experimentally and is known only with finite accuracy.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Thus, prior experiments that aimed to determine the numerical value of the Avogadro constant when expressed in reciprocal moles—i.e. the Avogadro number (now numerically fixed)—are re-interpreted as measurements of the numerical value in grams of the dalton.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] By the old definition of mole, the numerical value of the mass of one mole of a substance expressed in grams (i.e., its molar mass in g/mol or kg/kmol), was precisely equal to the average mass of one particle expressed in daltons.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] With the new definition, this numerical equivalence is no longer exact, as it is affected by the uncertainty in the value of the gram-to-dalton (g/Da) mass-unit ratio.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] However, it may still be assumed for all practical purposes.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] For example, the average mass of one molecule of water is about 18.0153 daltons, and an amount of one mole of water has a corresponding macroscopic mass of about 18.0153 grams.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Also, the Avogadro number is the approximate number of nucleons (protons and neutrons) in one gram of ordinary matter.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] An amount of substance consisting of just a single elementary entity might be thought of as an "elementary amount", analogous to the elementary charge, *e*.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Letting *n*a denote this elementary amount, then 1 mol = *N*0 *n*a.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] With the mole defined such that *N*A = *N*0/mol, this can be rearranged as 1 mol = *N*0/*N*A.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Thus, *n*a = 1/*N*A, the reciprocal of the Avogadro constant.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The fundamental definition of the Avogadro constant itself is therefore one per elementary amount (*N*A = 1/*n*a), independent of any macroscopic base unit chosen for the physical quantity.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Introducing *n*a in place of 1/*N*A, means that *n*(X) = *N*(X) *n*a—amount of substance is an aggregate of *N*(X) elementary entities—which is easier to comprehend than *N*(X) "reciprocal Avogadro constants".
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Also the molar mass is then *M*(X) = *m*(X)/*n*a—the entity mass per entity, which is self-evident.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] In older literature, the Avogadro number was also denoted N, although that conflicts with the symbol for number of particles in statistical mechanics.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The Avogadro constant is named after the Italian scientist Amedeo Avogadro (1776–1856), who, in 1811, first proposed that the volume of a gas (at a given pressure and temperature) is proportional to the number of atoms or molecules regardless of the nature of the gas.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Avogadro's hypothesis was popularized four years after his death by Stanislao Cannizzaro, who advocated Avogadro's work at the Karlsruhe Congress in 1860.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The name *Avogadro's number* was coined in 1909 by the physicist Jean Perrin, who defined it as the number of molecules in exactly 32 grams of oxygen gas.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] This definition numerically equates the mass of a mole of a substance, in grams, to the mass of one molecule relative to the mass of a hydrogen atom.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Because of the law of definite proportions, a hydrogen atom was the natural unit of atomic mass and was assumed to be ⁠1/16⁠ of the atomic mass of oxygen.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The value of Avogadro's number (not yet known by that name) was first obtained indirectly by Josef Loschmidt in 1865, by estimating the number of particles in a given volume of gas.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] where *p*0 is the pressure, *R* is the gas constant, and *T*0 is the absolute temperature.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Because of this work, the symbol *L* is sometimes used for the Avogadro constant, and, in German literature, that name may be used for both constants, distinguished only by the units of measurement.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Perrin himself determined the Avogadro number, which he called "Avogadro's constant" (constante d'Avogadro), by several different experimental methods.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] He was awarded the 1926 Nobel Prize in Physics, largely for this work.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The electric charge per mole of electrons is a constant called the Faraday constant and has been known since 1834, when Michael Faraday published his works on electrolysis.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] In 1910, Robert Millikan with the help of Harvey Fletcher obtained the first measurement of the charge on an electron.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Dividing the charge on a mole of electrons by the charge on a single electron provided a more accurate estimate of the Avogadro number.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] X-ray crystallography uses the diffraction of X-rays by a crystal to accurately measure the distances between layers in its lattice, from which the volume occupied by each atom can be determined.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The Avogadro Project used this technique to measure the unit cell dimensions of extremely pure single-crystal spheres of silicon-28, with the goal of a more accurate silicon-based definition of the Avogadro constant.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] In 1971, in its 14th conference, the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) decided to regard the amount of substance as an independent dimension of measurement, with the mole as its base unit in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Specifically, the mole was defined as the amount of a substance that contains as many elementary entities as there are atoms in 12 grams (0.012 kilograms) of carbon-12 (12C).
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Thus, in particular, an amount of one mole of carbon 12 had a corresponding mass that was *exactly* 12 grams of that element.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] By this definition, one mole of any substance contained exactly as many elementary entities as one mole of any other substance.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] However, this number *N*0 was a physical constant that had to be experimentally determined since it depended on the mass (in grams) of one atom of 12C, and therefore, it was known only to a limited number of decimal digits.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The common rule of thumb that "one gram of matter contains *N*0 nucleons" was exact for carbon-12, but slightly inexact for other elements and isotopes.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] In the same conference, the BIPM also named *N*A (the factor that related the amount of a substance to the corresponding number of particles) the "Avogadro *constant*".
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] However, the term "Avogadro number" continued to be used, especially in introductory works.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] As a consequence of this definition, *N*A was not a pure number, but had the quantity dimension of reciprocal of amount of substance (**N**−1).
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Before 2019, the mole was defined by the amount of substance in exactly 12 grams of carbon-12.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Effective 20 May 2019, the BIPM defined the Avogadro constant *N*A as the exact value 6.02214076×1023 mol−1, thus redefining the mole as the amount of a substance having exactly 6.02214076×1023 constituent particles of that substance.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] One consequence of this change is that the mass of a mole of 12C atoms is no longer exactly 0.012 kg.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] On the other hand, the dalton, Da (a.k.a. unified atomic mass unit, u), remains unchanged as ⁠1/12⁠ of the mass of 12C.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] Thus, the molar mass constant remains very close to but no longer exactly equal to 1 g/mol, although the difference (1.0×10−9 in relative terms for the CODATA 2022 recommended value) is insignificant for all practical purposes.
[src:pc-saft/avogadro-constant] The Avogadro constant *N*A is related to other physical constants and properties.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The **Boltzmann constant** (*k*B or k) is the proportionality factor that relates the average relative thermal energy of particles in a gas with the thermodynamic temperature of the gas.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] It occurs in the definitions of the kelvin (K) and the molar gas constant, in Planck's law of black-body radiation and Boltzmann's entropy formula, and is used in calculating thermal noise in resistors.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The Boltzmann constant has dimensions of energy divided by temperature, the same as entropy and heat capacity.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] It is named after the Austrian scientist Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] As part of the 2019 revision of the SI, the Boltzmann constant is one of the seven "defining constants" that have been defined so as to have exact finite decimal values in SI units.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] They are used in various combinations to define the seven SI base units.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The Boltzmann constant is defined to be exactly 1.380649×10−23 joules per kelvin, with the effect of defining the SI unit kelvin.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Macroscopically, the ideal gas law states that, for an ideal gas, the product of pressure p and volume V is proportional to the product of amount of substance n and absolute temperature T: $pV=nRT,$ where R is the molar gas constant (8.31446261815324 J⋅K−1⋅mol−1).
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Introducing the Boltzmann constant as the gas constant per molecule *k* = *R*/*N*A (*N*A being the Avogadro constant) transforms the ideal gas law into an alternative form: $pV=NkT,$ where N is the number of molecules of gas.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Given a thermodynamic system at an absolute temperature T, the average thermal energy carried by each microscopic degree of freedom in the system is ⁠1/2⁠ *kT* (i.e., about 2.07×10−21 J, or 0.013 eV, at room temperature).
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] This is generally true only for classical systems with a large number of particles.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] In classical statistical mechanics, this average is predicted to hold exactly for homogeneous ideal gases.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Monatomic ideal gases (the six noble gases) possess three degrees of freedom per atom, corresponding to the three spatial directions.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] According to the equipartition of energy this means that there is a thermal energy of ⁠3/2⁠ *kT* per atom.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] This corresponds very well with experimental data.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The thermal energy can be used to calculate the root-mean-square speed of the atoms, which turns out to be inversely proportional to the square root of the atomic mass.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The root mean square speeds found at room temperature accurately reflect this, ranging from 1370 m/s for helium, down to 240 m/s for xenon.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Considering that the translational motion velocity vector **v** has three degrees of freedom (one for each dimension) gives the average energy per degree of freedom equal to one third of that, i.e. ⁠1/2⁠ *kT*.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The ideal gas equation is also obeyed closely by molecular gases; but the form for the heat capacity is more complicated, because the molecules possess additional internal degrees of freedom, as well as the three degrees of freedom for movement of the molecule as a whole.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Diatomic gases, for example, possess a total of six degrees of simple freedom per molecule that are related to atomic motion (three translational, two rotational, and one vibrational).
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] At lower temperatures, not all these degrees of freedom may fully participate in the gas heat capacity, due to quantum mechanical limits on the availability of excited states at the relevant thermal energy per molecule.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] More generally, systems in equilibrium at temperature T have probability *P**i* of occupying a state i with energy E weighted by the corresponding Boltzmann factor: $P_{i}\propto {\frac {\exp \left(-{\frac {E}{kT}}\right)}{Z}},$ where Z is the partition function.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Again, it is the energy-like quantity *kT* that takes central importance.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Consequences of this include (in addition to the results for ideal gases above) the Arrhenius equation in chemical kinetics.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] This equation, which relates the microscopic details, or microstates, of the system (via W) to its macroscopic state (via the entropy S), is the central idea of statistical mechanics.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Such is its importance that it is inscribed on Boltzmann's tombstone.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] This is a more natural form and this rescaled entropy corresponds exactly to Shannon's information entropy.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The characteristic energy kT is thus the energy required to increase the rescaled entropy by one nat.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] In semiconductors, the Shockley diode equation—the relationship between the flow of electric current and the electrostatic potential across a p–n junction—depends on a characteristic voltage called the *thermal voltage*, denoted by *V*T.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The thermal voltage depends on absolute temperature T as $V_{\mathrm {T} }={kT \over q}={RT \over F},$ where q is the magnitude of the electrical charge on the electron with a value 1.602176634×10−19 C.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The thermal voltage is also important in plasmas and electrolyte solutions (e.g. the Nernst equation); in both cases it provides a measure of how much the spatial distribution of electrons or ions is affected by a boundary held at a fixed voltage.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The Boltzmann constant is named after its 19th century Austrian discoverer, Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Before 1900, equations involving Boltzmann factors were not written using the energies per molecule and the Boltzmann constant, but rather using a form of the gas constant R, and macroscopic energies for macroscopic quantities of the substance.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The iconic terse form of the equation *S* = *k* ln *W* on Boltzmann's tombstone is in fact due to Planck, not Boltzmann.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Planck actually introduced it in the same work as his eponymous h.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] This "peculiar state of affairs" is illustrated by reference to one of the great scientific debates of the time.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] There was considerable disagreement in the second half of the nineteenth century as to whether atoms and molecules were real or whether they were simply a heuristic tool for solving problems.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] There was no agreement whether *chemical* molecules, as measured by atomic weights, were the same as *physical* molecules, as measured by kinetic theory.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] In versions of SI prior to the 2019 revision of the SI, the Boltzmann constant was a measured quantity rather than having a fixed numerical value.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Its exact definition also varied over the years due to redefinitions of the kelvin (see *Kelvin § History*) and other SI base units (see *Joule § History*).
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] In 2017, the most accurate measures of the Boltzmann constant were obtained by acoustic gas thermometry, which determines the speed of sound of a monatomic gas in a triaxial ellipsoid chamber using microwave and acoustic resonances.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] This decade-long effort was undertaken with different techniques by several laboratories; it is one of the cornerstones of the revision of the SI.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Based on these measurements, the value of 1.380649×10−23 J/K was recommended as the final fixed value of the Boltzmann constant to be used for the 2019 revision of the SI.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] As a precondition for redefining the Boltzmann constant, there must be one experimental value with a relative uncertainty below 1 ppm, and at least one measurement from a second technique with a relative uncertainty below 3 ppm.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The acoustic gas thermometry reached 0.2 ppm, and Johnson noise thermometry reached 2.8 ppm.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] Since k is a proportionality constant between temperature and energy, its numerical value depends on the choice of units for energy and temperature.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The small numerical value of the Boltzmann constant in SI units means a change in temperature by 1 K changes a particle's energy by only a small amount.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] A change of 1 °C is defined to be the same as a change of 1 K.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The characteristic energy *kT* is a term encountered in many physical relationships.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The Boltzmann constant sets up a relationship between wavelength and temperature (dividing *hc*/*k* by a wavelength gives a temperature) with 1000 nm being related to 14387.777 K, and also a relationship between voltage and temperature, with one volt corresponding to 11604.518 K.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] The Boltzmann constant provides a mapping from the characteristic microscopic energy E to the macroscopic temperature scale *T* = ⁠*E*/*k*⁠.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] In fundamental physics, this mapping is often simplified by using the natural units of setting k to unity.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] This convention means that temperature and energy quantities have the same dimensions.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] In particular, the SI unit kelvin becomes superfluous, being defined in terms of joules as 1 K = 1.380649×10−23 J.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] With this convention, temperature is always given in units of energy, and the Boltzmann constant is not explicitly needed in formulas.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] This convention simplifies many physical relationships and formulas.
[src:pc-saft/boltzmann-constant] As another example, the definition of thermodynamic entropy coincides with the form of information entropy: $S=-\sum _{i}P_{i}\ln P_{i}.$ where *P**i* is the probability of each microstate.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In physics and chemistry, an **equation of state** is a thermodynamic equation relating state variables, which describe the state of matter under a given set of physical conditions, such as pressure, volume, temperature, or internal energy.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Most modern equations of state are formulated in the Helmholtz free energy.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Equations of state are useful in describing the properties of pure substances and mixtures in liquids, gases, and solid states as well as the state of matter in the interior of stars.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Though there are many equations of state, none accurately predicts properties of substances under all conditions.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The quest for a universal equation of state has spanned three centuries.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] At present, there is no single equation of state that accurately predicts the properties of all substances under all conditions.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] An example of an equation of state correlates densities of gases and liquids to temperatures and pressures, known as the ideal gas law, which is roughly accurate for weakly polar gases at low pressures and moderate temperatures.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] This equation becomes increasingly inaccurate at higher pressures and lower temperatures, and fails to predict condensation from a gas to a liquid.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] where p is the pressure, V the volume, and T the temperature of the system.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Yet also other variables may be used in that form.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] It is directly related to Gibbs phase rule, that is, the number of independent variables depends on the number of substances and phases in the system.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] An equation used to model this relationship is called an equation of state.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In most cases this model will comprise some empirical parameters that are usually adjusted to measurement data.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Equations of state can also describe solids, including the transition of solids from one crystalline state to another.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Equations of state are also used for the modeling of the state of matter in the interior of stars, including neutron stars, dense matter (quark–gluon plasmas) and radiation fields.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] A related concept is the perfect fluid equation of state used in cosmology.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Equations of state are applied in many fields such as process engineering and petroleum industry as well as pharmaceutical industry.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Any consistent set of units may be used, although SI units are preferred.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Absolute temperature refers to the use of the Kelvin (K), with zero being absolute zero.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Boyle's law was one of the earliest formulation of an equation of state.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In 1662, the Irish physicist and chemist Robert Boyle performed a series of experiments employing a J-shaped glass tube, which was sealed on one end.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Mercury was added to the tube, trapping a fixed quantity of air in the short, sealed end of the tube.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Then the volume of gas was measured as additional mercury was added to the tube.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The pressure of the gas could be determined by the difference between the mercury level in the short end of the tube and that in the long, open end.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Through these experiments, Boyle noted that the gas volume varied inversely with the pressure.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In mathematical form, this can be stated as: $pV=\mathrm {constant} .$ The above relationship has also been attributed to Edme Mariotte and is sometimes referred to as Mariotte's law.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] However, Mariotte's work was not published until 1676.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In 1787 the French physicist Jacques Charles found that oxygen, nitrogen, hydrogen, carbon dioxide, and air expand to roughly the same extent over the same 80-kelvin interval.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Mathematically, this can be represented for n species as: $p_{\text{total}}=p_{1}+p_{2}+\cdots +p_{n}=\sum _{i=1}^{n}p_{i}.$ In 1834, Émile Clapeyron combined Boyle's law and Charles' law into the first statement of the *ideal gas law*.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Initially, the law was formulated as *pVm* = *R*(*TC* + 267) (with temperature expressed in degrees Celsius), where *R* is the gas constant.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] However, later work revealed that the number should actually be closer to 273.2, and then the Celsius scale was defined with $0~^{\circ }\mathrm {C} =273.15~\mathrm {K}$ , giving: $pV_{m}=R\left(T_{C}+273.15\ {}^{\circ }{\text{C}}\right).$ In 1873, J.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] D. van der Waals introduced the first equation of state derived by the assumption of a finite volume occupied by the constituent molecules.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] His new formula revolutionized the study of equations of state, and was the starting point of cubic equations of state, which most famously continued via the Redlich–Kwong equation of state and the Soave modification of Redlich-Kwong.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] $\left(P+a{\frac {1}{V_{m}^{2}}}\right)(V_{m}-b)=RT$ where a is a parameter describing the attractive energy between particles and b is a parameter describing the volume of the particles.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Since for atomic and molecular gases, the classical ideal gas law is well suited in most cases, let us describe the equation of state for elementary particles with mass m and spin s that takes into account quantum effects.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In the following, the upper sign will always correspond to Fermi–Dirac statistics and the lower sign to Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In the limiting case where $e^{\mu /(k_{\text{B}}T)}\ll 1$ , this equation of state will reduce to that of the classical ideal gas.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The quantum nature of this equation is in its dependence on s and **ħ**.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Cubic equations of state are called such because they can be rewritten as a cubic function of $V_{m}$ .
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Cubic equations of state originated from the van der Waals equation of state.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Hence, all cubic equations of state can be considered 'modified van der Waals equation of state'.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] There is a very large number of such cubic equations of state.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] For process engineering, cubic equations of state are today still highly relevant, e.g. the Peng Robinson equation of state or the Soave Redlich Kwong equation of state.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Although usually not the most convenient equation of state, the virial equation is important because it can be derived directly from statistical mechanics.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] This equation is also called the Kamerlingh Onnes equation.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] If appropriate assumptions are made about the mathematical form of intermolecular forces, theoretical expressions can be developed for each of the coefficients.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] *A* is the first virial coefficient, which has a constant value of 1 and makes the statement that when volume is large, all fluids behave like ideal gases.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The second virial coefficient *B* corresponds to interactions between pairs of molecules, *C* to triplets, and so on.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Accuracy can be increased indefinitely by considering higher order terms.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The coefficients *B*, *C*, *D*, etc. are functions of temperature only.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Values of the various parameters can be found in reference materials.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The BWR equation of state has also frequently been used for the modelling of the Lennard-Jones fluid.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] There are several extensions and modifications of the classical BWR equation of state available.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Note that in this virial equation, the fourth and fifth virial terms are zero.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The second virial coefficient is monotonically decreasing as temperature is lowered.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The third virial coefficient is monotonically increasing as temperature is lowered.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The Lee–Kesler equation of state is based on the corresponding states principle, and is a modification of the BWR equation of state.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] There is a large number of physically based equations of state available today.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Most of those are formulated in the Helmholtz free energy as a function of temperature, density (and for mixtures additionally the composition).
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The Helmholtz energy is formulated as a sum of multiple terms modelling different types of molecular interaction or molecular structures, e.g. the formation of chains or dipolar interactions.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Hence, physically based equations of state model the effect of molecular size, attraction and shape as well as hydrogen bonding and polar interactions of fluids.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In general, physically based equations of state give more accurate results than traditional cubic equations of state, especially for systems containing liquids or solids.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Most physically based equations of state are built on monomer term describing the Lennard-Jones fluid or the Mie fluid.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Perturbation theory is frequently used for modelling dispersive interactions in an equation of state.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] There is a large number of perturbation theory based equations of state available today, e.g. for the classical Lennard-Jones fluid.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The two most important theories used for these types of equations of state are the Barker-Henderson perturbation theory and the Weeks–Chandler–Andersen perturbation theory.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The SAFT equation of state was developed using statistical mechanical methods (in particular the perturbation theory of Wertheim) to describe the interactions between molecules in a system.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The idea of a SAFT equation of state was first proposed by Chapman et al. in 1988 and 1989.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Many different versions of the SAFT models have been proposed, but all use the same chain and association terms derived by Chapman et al.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Multiparameter equations of state are empirical equations of state that can be used to represent pure fluids with high accuracy.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Multiparameter equations of state are empirical correlations of experimental data and are usually formulated in the Helmholtz free energy.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The functional form of these models is in most parts not physically motivated.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] They can be usually applied in both liquid and gaseous states.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Empirical multiparameter equations of state represent the Helmholtz energy of the fluid as the sum of ideal gas and residual terms.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The reduced density $\rho _{r}$ and reduced temperature $T_{r}$ are in most cases the critical values for the pure fluid.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Because integration of the multiparameter equations of state is not required and thermodynamic properties can be determined using classical thermodynamic relations, there are few restrictions as to the functional form of the ideal or residual terms.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Typical multiparameter equations of state use upwards of 50 fluid specific parameters, but are able to represent the fluid's properties with high accuracy.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Multiparameter equations of state are available currently for about 50 of the most common industrial fluids including refrigerants.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The IAPWS95 reference equation of state for water is also a multiparameter equations of state.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Mixture models for multiparameter equations of state exist, as well.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Yet, multiparameter equations of state applied to mixtures are known to exhibit artifacts at times.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] One example of such an equation of state is the form proposed by Span and Wagner.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] This is a somewhat simpler form that is intended to be used more in technical applications.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Equations of state that require a higher accuracy use a more complicated form with more terms.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] where e is the internal energy per unit mass, $\gamma$ is an empirically determined constant typically taken to be about 6.1, and $p^{0}$ is another constant, representing the molecular attraction between water molecules.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The magnitude of the correction is about 2 gigapascals (20,000 atmospheres).
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The equation is stated in this form because the speed of sound in water is given by $c^{2}=\gamma \left(p+p^{0}\right)/\rho$ .
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] This equation mispredicts the specific heat capacity of water but few simple alternatives are available for severely nonisentropic processes such as strong shocks.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The Landau–Stanyukovich–Zeldovich–Kompaneets equation of state (often abbreviated LSZK EOS) is a thermodynamic model used to describe the pressure–energy relationship of detonation products and high‑pressure reactive gases in computational hydrodynamics and explosive physics.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] It is named after prominent Soviet physicists Lev Landau & K.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] Stanyukovich (1945),[1] and Yakov Zeldovich & Alexander Kompaneyets (1960).[2] The LSZK EOS is primarily used to model detonation products rather than the unreacted solid explosive itself.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] It provides a smooth pressure–energy relationship suitable for numerical simulations of blast waves and shock propagation.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] where $\gamma$ is the specific heat ratio and $p_{shift}$ is a pressure offset to account for non-ideal behavior of real detonation gases.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] An ultrarelativistic fluid has equation of state $p=\rho _{m}c_{s}^{2}$ where p is the pressure, $\rho _{m}$ is the mass density, and $c_{s}$ is the speed of sound.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The ratio $V=\rho _{e}/\rho$ is defined by using $\rho _{e}$ , which is the density of the explosive (solid part) and $\rho$ , which is the density of the detonation products.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] The parameters A , B , $R_{1}$ , $R_{2}$ and $\omega$ are given by several references.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] In addition, the initial density (solid part) $\rho _{0}$ , speed of detonation $V_{D}$ , Chapman–Jouguet pressure $P_{CJ}$ and the chemical energy per unit volume of the explosive $e_{0}$ are given in such references.
[src:pc-saft/equation-of-state] These parameters are obtained by fitting the JWL-EOS to experimental results.
