[src:pc-saft/gabriele-sadowski] Sadowski studied chemistry at Technische Universität Leuna-Merseburg from 1982 to 1987.
[src:pc-saft/gabriele-sadowski] She finished her doctorate in 1991 at Technische Universität Leuna-Merseburg.
[src:pc-saft/gabriele-sadowski] She completed her dissertation at Technische Universität Berlin in 2000.
[src:pc-saft/gabriele-sadowski] Her research focuses on Polymer Thermodynamics, Thermodynamics of Pharmaceutical Systems, and Reaction Thermodynamics.
[src:pc-saft/gabriele-sadowski] Since 2001, she is full professor at TU Dortmund University.
[src:pc-saft/gabriele-sadowski] She took over the responsibility of prorector research in 2016.
[src:pc-saft/gabriele-sadowski] She was awarded the Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize in 2011 and she is a member of the North Rhine-Westphalian Academy of Sciences, Humanities and the Arts.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] In thermodynamics, the **Helmholtz free energy** (or **Helmholtz energy**) is a thermodynamic potential that measures the useful work obtainable from a closed thermodynamic system at a constant temperature (isothermal).
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The change in the Helmholtz energy during a process is equal to the maximum amount of work that the system can perform in a thermodynamic process in which temperature is held constant.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] At constant temperature, the Helmholtz free energy is minimized at equilibrium.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] In contrast, the Gibbs free energy or free enthalpy is most commonly used as a measure of thermodynamic potential (especially in chemistry) when it is convenient for applications that occur at constant *pressure*.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] For example, in explosives research Helmholtz free energy is often used, since explosive reactions by their nature induce pressure changes.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] It is also frequently used to define fundamental equations of state of pure substances.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The concept of free energy was developed by Hermann von Helmholtz, a German physicist, and first presented in 1882 in a lecture called "On the thermodynamics of chemical processes".
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] From the German word *Arbeit* (work), the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) recommends the symbol *A* and the name *Helmholtz energy*.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] In physics, the symbol *F* is also used in reference to *free energy* or *Helmholtz function*.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The Helmholtz energy is the Legendre transformation of the internal energy *U*, in which temperature replaces entropy as the independent variable.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The first law of thermodynamics in a closed system provides $\mathrm {d} U=\delta Q\ +\delta W,$ where U is the internal energy, $\delta Q$ is the energy added as heat, and $\delta W$ is the work done on the system.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The second law of thermodynamics for a reversible process yields $\delta Q=T\,\mathrm {d} S$ .
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Because *A* is a thermodynamic function of state, this relation is also valid for a process (without electrical work or composition change) that is not reversible.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The laws of thermodynamics are only directly applicable to systems in thermal equilibrium.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] If we wish to describe phenomena like chemical reactions, then the best we can do is to consider suitably chosen initial and final states in which the system is in (metastable) thermal equilibrium.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] If the system is kept at fixed volume and is in contact with a heat bath at some constant temperature, then we can reason as follows.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Since the thermodynamical variables of the system are well defined in the initial state and the final state, the internal energy increase $\Delta U$ , the entropy increase $\Delta S$ , and the total amount of work that can be extracted, performed by the system, W , are well defined quantities.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The volume of the system is kept constant.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] This means that the volume of the heat bath does not change either, and we can conclude that the heat bath does not perform any work.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The heat bath remains in thermal equilibrium at temperature *T* no matter what the system does.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Since the system is in thermal equilibrium with the heat bath in the initial and the final states, *T* is also the temperature of the system in these states.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] We see that the total amount of work that can be extracted in an isothermal process is limited by the free-energy decrease, and that increasing the free energy in a reversible process requires work to be done on the system.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] and thus for a system kept at constant temperature and volume and not capable of performing electrical or other non-*PV* work, the total free energy during a spontaneous change can only decrease.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] To allow for spontaneous processes at constant *T* and *V*, one needs to enlarge the thermodynamical state space of the system.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] In case of a chemical reaction, one must allow for changes in the numbers *N**j* of particles of each type *j*.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] where the $N_{j}$ are the numbers of particles of type j and the $\mu _{j}$ are the corresponding chemical potentials.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] This equation is then again valid for both reversible and non-reversible changes.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] In case of a spontaneous change at constant T and V, the last term will thus be negative.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Here the $x_{i}$ are the external variables, and the $X_{i}$ the corresponding generalized forces.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] A system kept at constant volume, temperature, and particle number is described by the canonical ensemble.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Suppose that the system has one external variable x .
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The value of *c* can be determined by considering the limit *T* → 0.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] In this limit the entropy becomes $S=k\log \Omega _{0}$ , where $\Omega _{0}$ is the ground-state degeneracy.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The partition function in this limit is $\Omega _{0}e^{-\beta U_{0}}$ , where $U_{0}$ is the ground-state energy.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] allow an efficient way of calculating thermodynamic variables of interest given the partition function and are often used in density of state calculations.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] One can also do Legendre transformations for different systems.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Computing the free energy is an intractable problem for all but the simplest models in statistical physics.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] A powerful approximation method is mean-field theory, which is a variational method based on the Bogoliubov inequality.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] This inequality can be formulated as follows.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Suppose we replace the real Hamiltonian H of the model by a trial Hamiltonian ${\tilde {H}}$ , which has different interactions and may depend on extra parameters that are not present in the original model.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] where A is the free energy of the original Hamiltonian, and ${\tilde {A}}$ is the free energy of the trial Hamiltonian.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] By including a large number of parameters in the trial Hamiltonian and minimizing the free energy, we can expect to get a close approximation to the exact free energy.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The Bogoliubov inequality is often applied in the following way.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Here we have defined $\langle X\rangle _{0}$ to be the average of *X* over the canonical ensemble defined by $H_{0}$ .
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] where $\langle X\rangle$ is still the average over ${\tilde {H}}$ , as specified above.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The free energy ${\tilde {A}}$ is the free energy of the model defined by $H_{0}$ plus $\langle \Delta H\rangle$ .
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] For a classical model we can prove the Bogoliubov inequality as follows.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] We denote the canonical probability distributions for the Hamiltonian and the trial Hamiltonian by $P_{r}$ and ${\tilde {P}}_{r}$ , respectively.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] To see this, consider the difference between the left hand side and the right hand side.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] where in the last step we have used that both probability distributions are normalized to 1.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] where the averages are taken with respect to ${\tilde {P}}_{r}$ .
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Here we have used that the partition functions are constants with respect to taking averages and that the free energy is proportional to minus the logarithm of the partition function.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] We can easily generalize this proof to the case of quantum mechanical models.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] We denote the eigenstates of ${\tilde {H}}$ by $\left|r\right\rangle$ .
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] still holds as both the $P_{r}$ and the ${\tilde {P}}_{r}$ sum to 1.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] for the expectation value of the operator Y in the state r.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] where $\sigma _{ij}$ is the stress tensor, and $\varepsilon _{ij}$ is the strain tensor.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] where we are now using Einstein notation for the tensors, in which repeated indices in a product are summed.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] The Helmholtz free energy function for a pure substance (together with its partial derivatives) can be used to determine all other thermodynamic properties for the substance.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] See, for example, the equations of state for water, as given by the IAPWS in their IAPWS-95 release.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Hinton and Zemel "derive an objective function for training auto-encoder based on the minimum description length (MDL) principle".
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] "The description length of an input vector using a particular code is the sum of the code cost and reconstruction cost.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] They define this to be the energy of the code.
[src:pc-saft/helmholtz-free-energy] Given an input vector, they define the energy of a code to be the sum of the code cost and the reconstruction cost." The true expected combined cost is $A=\sum _{i}p_{i}E_{i}-H,$ "which has exactly the form of Helmholtz free energy".
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] It is denoted ***xi*** (lowercase Roman letter *x*), sometimes **χi** (lowercase Greek letter chi).
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] It is a dimensionless quantity with dimension of ${\mathsf {N}}/{\mathsf {N}}$ and dimensionless unit of **moles per mole** (**mol/mol** or **mol⋅mol−1**) or simply 1; metric prefixes may also be used (e.g., nmol/mol for 10−9).
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] When expressed in percent, it is known as the **mole percent** or **molar percentage** (unit symbol %, sometimes "mol%", equivalent to cmol/mol for 10−2).
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] The mole fraction is called **amount fraction** by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) and **amount-of-substance fraction** by the U.S.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST).
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] This nomenclature is part of the International System of Quantities (ISQ), as standardized in ISO 80000-9, which deprecates "mole fraction" based on the unacceptability of mixing information with units when expressing the values of quantities.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] Mole fraction is numerically identical to the **number fraction**, which is defined as the number of particles (molecules) of a constituent *Ni* divided by the total number of all molecules *N*tot.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] Whereas mole fraction is a ratio of amounts to amounts (in units of moles per moles), molar concentration is a quotient of amount to volume (in units of moles per litre).
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] Other ways of expressing the composition of a mixture as a dimensionless quantity are mass fraction and volume fraction.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] Mole fraction is used very frequently in the construction of phase diagrams.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] This equality can be rearranged to have differential quotient of mole amounts or fractions on one side.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] where *Mi* is the molar mass of the component *i* and *M̄* is the average molar mass of the mixture.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] The mixing of two pure components can be expressed introducing the amount or molar mixing ratio of them $r_{n}={\frac {n_{2}}{n_{1}}}$ .
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] due to division of both numerator and denominator by the sum of molar amounts of components.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] This property has consequences for representations of phase diagrams using, for instance, ternary plots.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] Mixing binary mixtures with a common component gives a ternary mixture with certain mixing ratios between the three components.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] Multiplying mole fraction by 100 gives the mole percentage, also referred as amount/amount percent [abbreviated as (n/n)% or mol %].
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] where *M̄* is the average molar mass of the mixture.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] where *M̄* is the average molar mass of the solution, *c* is the total molar concentration and *ρ* is the density of the solution.
[src:pc-saft/mole-fraction] In a spatially non-uniform mixture, the mole fraction gradient triggers the phenomenon of diffusion.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] His education in science and mathematics began at St.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] Pius X High School in Houston, Texas, and continued with engineering and science studies at the University of Houston, where he earned a Bachelor of Science degree in chemical engineering in 1965.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] During his undergraduate studies, Professor H.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] Prengle guided him in the fundamentals of thermodynamics and equations of state.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] After graduation, he worked with Dow Chemical Company Research and Development, where he was mentored by Dr.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] In 1968, Carnahan began graduate studies at the University of Oklahoma.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] His graduate advisor was Professor Kenneth Earl Starling.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] During his graduate studies, he was influenced by Professors Sherrill D.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] Christian, Jack Cohn and Cedomir Sliepcevich, and by correspondences with Berni Alder, Bill Hoover, E.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] Carnahan's vision of molecular interactions and fluid behavior was strongly influenced by the works of Johannes Diderik van der Waals and by René Descartes.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] After completion of his doctoral studies at University of Oklahoma, in 1971, he began a long research and teaching association with Professors Riki Kobayashi and Thomas W.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] Leland Jr., at Rice University in Houston, Texas.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] In the 1980s, he resumed work on extending the Carnahan-Starling equation of state to systems of rigid non-attracting non-spherical particles.
[src:pc-saft/norman-f-carnahan] Muller, a series of papers were published in which a shape factor concept was incorporated to enable the equation developed for rigid sphere fluids to be extended to describe the fluid phase of many rigid nonattracting nonspherical particles.
[src:pc-saft/pc-saft] PC-SAFT was developed by Joachim Gross and Gabriele Sadowski, and was first presented in their 2001 article.
[src:pc-saft/pc-saft] Further research extended PC-SAFT for use with associating and polar molecules, and it has also been modified for use with polymers.
[src:pc-saft/pc-saft] A version of PC-SAFT has also been developed to describe mixtures with ionic compounds (called electrolyte PC-SAFT or ePC-SAFT).
[src:pc-saft/pc-saft] The equation is most often expressed in terms of the residual Helmholtz energy because all other thermodynamic properties can be easily found by taking the appropriate derivatives of the Helmholtz energy.
